That's how I'm gonna survive.

27
00:01:24,173 --> 00:01:26,054
So I wanna frame the conversation a little bit

28
00:01:26,094 --> 00:01:27,474
around what I mean when I'm talking about

29
00:01:27,514 --> 00:01:28,695
the unmanageable project.

30
00:01:28,835 --> 00:01:30,876
Because it could be an entire game project,

31
00:01:31,396 --> 00:01:32,977
or it could be a piece of a project.

32
00:01:33,357 --> 00:01:34,738
It could be a critical feature

33
00:01:34,838 --> 00:01:37,059
that needs to go out really quickly.

34
00:01:37,719 --> 00:01:39,880
It could be a piece of the content pipeline

35
00:01:39,900 --> 00:01:41,621
that's really screwed up and is potentially

36
00:01:41,701 --> 00:01:43,862
dragging down the schedule of the entire project.

37
00:01:44,821 --> 00:01:48,722
Or it could be a demo, like a demo for GDC, for example.

38
00:01:48,762 --> 00:01:51,183
I'm sure a lot of you have had demo deadlines

39
00:01:51,203 --> 00:01:53,803
that you've been dealing with, or E3, or PACS.

40
00:01:54,904 --> 00:01:56,984
So it could be any one of a number of things.

41
00:01:57,944 --> 00:02:01,005
But in the context of the unmanageable project,

42
00:02:01,105 --> 00:02:03,826
it usually tends to meet three additional criteria.

43
00:02:05,622 --> 00:02:08,063
So one is that these projects tend to be high risk

44
00:02:08,403 --> 00:02:11,045
and therefore present a clear opportunity for failure.

45
00:02:11,065 --> 00:02:13,026
I know a lot of you probably think,

46
00:02:13,066 --> 00:02:15,607
well, all projects present a clear opportunity for failure,

47
00:02:15,647 --> 00:02:16,948
but that's not necessarily true.

48
00:02:17,048 --> 00:02:18,649
I've been on a lot of projects where

49
00:02:18,669 --> 00:02:23,311
it's not the end of the world if you're a little bit late

50
00:02:23,731 --> 00:02:24,992
or if you're a little bit over budget,

51
00:02:25,272 --> 00:02:27,093
but in some cases, it is the end of the world.

52
00:02:29,512 --> 00:02:32,955
So another hallmark is that they're often heavily resource

53
00:02:33,015 --> 00:02:33,635
constrained.

54
00:02:33,935 --> 00:02:36,177
And in the context of this particular conversation,

55
00:02:36,217 --> 00:02:38,478
the resource I'm talking about specifically is time.

56
00:02:38,918 --> 00:02:40,119
Because you can always add people,

57
00:02:40,379 --> 00:02:41,280
you can always add budget.

58
00:02:41,780 --> 00:02:43,781
But when you can't add time, sometimes that

59
00:02:43,821 --> 00:02:45,643
presents a particular set of challenges.

60
00:02:48,384 --> 00:02:51,606
And there are also clear consequences for failure.

61
00:02:52,027 --> 00:02:54,708
So this could be anything from you

62
00:02:54,749 --> 00:02:56,189
don't launch the project on time,

63
00:02:56,269 --> 00:02:57,290
you might not get a promotion.

64
00:02:58,027 --> 00:03:00,489
or maybe your team won't get their bonus,

65
00:03:00,650 --> 00:03:02,071
or maybe your team will be fired,

66
00:03:02,852 --> 00:03:05,154
or maybe the project will be defunded.

67
00:03:05,415 --> 00:03:07,677
So there's usually pretty clear consequences

68
00:03:08,378 --> 00:03:10,640
to a project going sideways of this type.

69
00:03:13,617 --> 00:03:16,100
So if you haven't already been handed one of these,

70
00:03:16,120 --> 00:03:18,423
I just have to say brace yourself

71
00:03:18,503 --> 00:03:20,386
because if you spend any amount of time

72
00:03:20,446 --> 00:03:21,507
in the games industry,

73
00:03:22,288 --> 00:03:24,391
you will be put in charge of one of these projects,

74
00:03:24,471 --> 00:03:26,834
a chaotic project with a crazy deadline,

75
00:03:27,214 --> 00:03:29,517
and it's gonna be your job to get it back on track.

76
00:03:29,617 --> 00:03:30,558
So that's the bad news.

77
00:03:31,339 --> 00:03:35,460
The good news is I've spent many years of my career running these kinds of projects,

78
00:03:35,540 --> 00:03:40,022
and I have to say, in my experience, there's always a way to figure out how to get a project

79
00:03:40,062 --> 00:03:44,723
back on track, as long as you're willing to adopt a particular mindset to make that happen.

80
00:03:45,543 --> 00:03:48,944
And that mindset, I also want to add, does not always necessarily involve crunch.

81
00:03:49,724 --> 00:03:51,205
So we'll talk about that a little bit later.

82
00:03:53,335 --> 00:03:55,235
So this is probably a good point to introduce myself.

83
00:03:55,275 --> 00:03:56,216
My name is Amy Dallas.

84
